referred_to_by.content: very large head of the Buddha in cast iron, with downcast eyes and meditative expression.  The hair is upswept in neat ridges and tied at the top of the head.  The cranial protuberance and extended earlobes are physical attributes that are typical of representations of the Buddha.  The surface of the head show seams of the mold in which it was originally cast.

referred_to_by.content: Functioning Cipollino marble fountain.  The upper bowl is carved with mermaid and dolphin motif with an octagonal pedestal base.  A finely modelled bronze standing fountain figure of "The Verrocchio Boy" holding a dolphin in his arms is situated at the top center of the upper bowl with right leg lifted to the side and bent at the knee slight to the back and the left support leg is on a domed base.  The lower bowl, pool-surround is of Sicilian marble exhibiting rounded edges.

Description of the Object
referred_to_by.content: steel welded sculpture of the word "LOVE" with the "L" stacked on the "V" and the tilted "O" stacked on the "E".  Each component was fabricated from 3/16 inch thick sheets of Cor-ten steel.  The sheets were cut, welded together and then finished to create hollow, enclosed structures.   Each letter is 72 inches deep.  Components are secured together by a bolting system.  Specifically there are 2 sets of four bolts drilled along the one set and located along the proper left serif of "V" connecting to the upper proper right serif of "E".  The other is located at the proper left serif of "L" connecting to the proper right middle of "O".   Access panels enable entry for the bolts to be put in place.  Once access panel exists along the entire upper surface of the proper left "L" serif; there are two others atop the proper right side of the "E".  Central pivot points align the "O" over the "E".  Two points about 2-3 inches in height are permanently attached to the "E".

referred_to_by._label: Mark Description of the Object
referred_to_by.content: Stamped, lower proper right edge of the "E" along the full length: 1 [gapped]  [copyright symbol] R INDIANA  [in stencilled font] 1970  [HF symbol for Herbert Feuerlicht, Technical Supervisor of Triad Designs] [three stacked lines of smaller text] WORK EXECUTED BY  |  Lippincott  |  NORTH HAVEN CONN

referred_to_by._label: IMA at Newfields Creation Notes about the Object
referred_to_by.content: 06/23/2016 Per Alfred Lippincott, "...technical supervisor, Herbert Feuerlicht, of Triad Designs...this accounts for the large HF that is stamped into the metal just to the left of the Lippincott stamp..."

referred_to_by._label: Notes about the Materials of Which the Object is Composed
Description of the Object
referred_to_by.content: Sandstone Pierced Screen:  This screen consists of carvings from India collected by Mr. Lockwood de Forest and assembled to suggest a palace façade of that country.  In Bombay, Ahmedabad, and other Indian cities, are old houses in great number, with elaborate and beautiful carved fronts.  Almost the entire upper part of this screen is from such a house front in Ahmedabad.  Carvers in India are all of the Mistre or carpenter cast, and all, even the lowest of them in remote villages, seem born with a remarkable instinct for this art.  The children begin to learn the trade at three years old.  Boys of eight to twelve years carve nearly as well as the men.  The details of the carvings evolve as the carver works.  Only a few leading lines are sketched on the wood before the cutting begins.  Parts of this collection are ancient originals, others are accurate copies made by Indian workmen.  Some stone panels, pierced brasses and inlays are also included.

referred_to_by.content: Commissioned in Agra by Lockwood de Forest for Tiffany and de Forest
